cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.GT, cs.NE, cs.PL

Reasoning: 
1. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) - The paper presents a chess program that uses machine learning techniques to improve its performance. This falls under the domain of AI.
2. cs.LG (Machine Learning) - The paper introduces a variation of the TD(lambda) algorithm to enable it to be used in conjunction with game-tree search. This is a machine learning technique and hence falls under this category.
3. cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) - The paper discusses the use of game-tree search in the context of chess and how it can be combined with machine learning techniques to improve performance. This falls under the domain of game theory.
4. cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) - Although the paper does not explicitly mention the use of neural networks or evolutionary algorithms, the TD(lambda) algorithm is a reinforcement learning technique that is often used in conjunction with these methods. Hence, this category is also likely.
5. cs.PL (Programming Languages) - While the paper does not focus on programming languages, it does discuss the implementation of the TDLeaf(lambda) algorithm in the KnightCap chess program. Hence, this category is also a possibility.
